Congratulations, #Zambia, on launching #malaria vaccination to protect over half a million children: https://t.co/Fo5UBDy0oT

Malaria is one of 🇿🇲’s leading causes of illness and death, particularly among children under five.

@WHO will continue to support the government, health workers and communities to #EndMalaria and offer a healthier future for every child.

Amid violence and widespread cholera, #Sudan is also fighting a #dengue outbreak. The hardest-hit states are Khartoum, Al Jazirah and White Nile. So far, more than 37,000 people have been affected, and over 100 have died. 

@WHO is supporting the coordination of the response, including disease surveillance, case management and community engagement.

With the Health Ministry, in Khartoum we have mobilised 7800 volunteers to carry out these critical response activities to reach 936,000 households.

Many countries in the @WHOWPRO region are:
- taking action against tobacco and noncommunicable diseases;
- protecting girls against cervical cancer;
- expanding treatment for neglected tropical diseases;
- taking action against antimicrobial resistance;
- strengthening their emergency preparedness and response capacities.

The #ClimateCrisis remains an existential threat, so the Regional implementation plan for climate change and health system safety and resilience is an important step forward, especially for small island states.

In my address to the #RCM76, I called on Health Ministers to: 
1. Engage actively in negotiations on the PABS annex to the Pandemic Agreement to ensure equitable access to vaccines and other tools, and to conclude it in time for next year’s World Health Assembly in May.
2. Generate financing for health, and improve efficiency, as they build a more self-reliant future, free from aid dependency. 
3. Work with us to build a stronger, more empowered and more independent @WHO, that is better able to serve all countries.
 
I’m delighted to see the Regional Committee returning to the Pacific for the first time in a decade and I thank #Fiji for hosting it.

Health is a human right — and if countries truly believe in it, they can make progress towards achieving #HealthForAll, no matter their economic status.

Countries impacted by the sudden foreign aid cuts are turning this crisis into an opportunity to mobilize domestic resources and build self reliant health systems. They need our support in capacity building and fair terms for investment, trade and loans.

@WHO has also been undertaking sustainable financing reforms since 2017 — Member States have increased their annual fees, we have established the @WHOFoundation and held an Investment Round. We are also proposing to establish an endowment fund, which would ensure full financial independence. I called on #WHS2025 participants to help us make it happen!

