The confirmation of the ceasefire agreement in #Gaza brings fresh hope not only for millions of Palestinians, but also for families in #Israel desperately waiting for their loved ones to finally be released.

@WHO will continue focusing on maintaining health care services in Gaza, while working to support health workers and rebuilding the health system for early recovery and long-term resilience.

We call for: 
-unimpeded humanitarian access to scale up delivery of medical supplies, and for emergency medical teams to reach points of care; 
-medical evacuation corridors to be established for critical patients needing treatment outside Gaza;
-unimpeded access to expand mental health services across Gaza.

Let us now honor our promises and work together for long-lasting peace. Peace is the best medicine.

I welcome @POTUS’s announcement about the ceasefire in #Gaza and hostage release — it is indeed a big step towards lasting peace for both Israelis and Palestinians. I hope all parties will respect the agreement, so the suffering of all civilians finally ends and all hostages are brought home respectfully.

@WHO stands ready to scale up its work to meet the dire health needs of patients across Gaza, and to support rehabilitation of the destroyed health system. 

The best medicine is peace.

While millions of people are quitting tobacco or choosing not to start, 1 in 5 adults remain addicted: https://t.co/b1IPnMxPJ3

In response to this progress, the tobacco industry is fighting back with new nicotine products, such as vapes, aggressively targeting young people.

@WHO urges governments to act faster and stronger to implement proven tobacco control policies.

The evidence of @TheLancet EAT 2.0 Commission is clear: our food systems are inequitable, failing people and harming our planet.  

@WHO is working with countries to transform food environments, reduce harmful marketing to children, and tackle the growing burden of ultra-processed foods.  

I commend #Sweden for co-hosting @EATforum, and for its leadership on sustainable food systems.

6 out of 10 people in the world don't have access to safe, quality and affordable medical oxygen when needed.

@WHO's Access to #Oxygen Initiative supports countries to increase their ability to provide medical oxygen to their people.

On #WorldOxygenDay, we highlight the need for better access to medical oxygen, equipment and infrastructure, and a trained workforce to ensure #HealthForAll.

My thanks to Deputy President @PMashatile and Health Minister Aaron Motsoaledi for the opportunity to address #SAAIDS2025. 

I commend #SouthAfrica for its commitments to strengthen domestic funding for HIV and tuberculosis. 

@WHO remains committed to working with you for the health and well-being of all South Africans.

Happy 30th anniversary, @hug_ge!

Together, we have worked to translate scientific excellence into global health impact, strengthening public health policies and clinical practices worldwide.

@WHO looks forward to continuing our partnership, advancing healthcare, and improving the lives of people everywhere.

A new #Ebola outbreak is confirmed in the #DRC. Tragically, 15 deaths have been reported so far, including 4 health workers.

@WHO teams are already supporting the response, deploying experts and medical supplies needed to protect health workers and care for patients.

https://t.co/DprmJ0DzSK

#OnThisDay four years ago, former Chancellor Merkel and I launched the @WHO Pandemic and Epidemic Intelligence Hub in Berlin. 

Today, the Hub supports over 150 countries and 210 partner organizations to rapidly detect and respond to health threats, through several key initiatives and projects:
-Epidemic Intelligence from Open Sources tool to detect health threats in real-time by continuously scanning open sources and leveraging artificial intelligence;
-International Pathogen Surveillance Network jointly strengthening pathogen genomics surveillance in low- and middle-income countries;
-The Collaboratory promoting global collaboration on outbreak analytics and connects more than 1200 analysts and data scientists from over 100 institutions in more than 60 countries; 
-Supporting over 105 Member States to strengthen their national public health agencies for health emergencies preparedness and response.

Vielen Dank, #Germany, for your continued support and investment in global health!

#Cholera remains a major public health threat in Africa, with over 213,500 suspected cases and over 4,400 deaths just in 2025.

To tackle this threat, I joined President @HHichilema and @Dr_JeanKaseya in launching the continental preparedness and response plan against cholera, aiming to:
1. Reduce deaths by 90%;
2. Eliminate cholera in 20+ countries in the region;
3. Strengthen preparedness, surveillance and regional collaboration;
4. Drive the whole continent towards elimination by 2030.

Political commitment and leadership are key to bring this plan into reality. Together! #RC75

The devastating floods in #Pakistan have affected many people — I extend my deepest condolences to those who lost loved ones.

@WHO is supporting the government to meet health needs, and has sent medical supplies to treat 15,000 people.

https://t.co/n6GET0dYrO

Thinking of all the people in #CapeVerde's São Vicente and Santo Antão islands affected by the catastrophic floods. I express my solidarity with all the responders.

@WHO stands ready to support delivery of health care.

https://t.co/oj0rIgUIN1

Today is International Day of the World’s Indigenous Peoples.

@WHO is committed to working in partnership with Indigenous Peoples to advance their right to health: https://t.co/LyojwLHfx0

#IndigenousDay #HealthForAll https://t.co/NAG257yovq

Member States - State Parties to the International Health Regulations (2005) - have the right to decide whether or not to adopt and, subsequently, implement amendments to the IHR. We regret the US decision to reject the amendments adopted by consensus by the World Health Assembly in 2024 — including by the US, as the US played an active role in developing and negotiating those amendments together with other countries.

Hence, I wish to correct inaccuracies stated by @SecKennedy and @SecRubio:
- the 2024 amendments were proposed, negotiated and adopted by Member States, based on the learnings from the COVID-19 pandemic; 
- ⁠the 2024 amendments are not about empowering WHO, but about improving cooperation among Member States in the next pandemic; 
- the 2024 amendments are clear about Member States sovereignty. WHO has never had the power to mandate lockdowns, travel restrictions or other such measures - Member States have the power to do so if they see the need. 
- risk communication is an essential part of any emergency response, as populations need to be informed in a timely way. Using disease outbreaks for propaganda would be destructive and disastrous;
- WHO is impartial and works with all countries to improve people’s health. Here is the timeline of the WHO COVID-19 response: https://t.co/rs4vEo7QGF

Like the US, WHO would like to see better and stronger cooperation among countries in tackling current and future health threats. The world’s nations came together to create such a system when they created WHO, and they continue to support this system.

As the #IAS2025 starts today, @WHO remains steadfast in our commitment to achieving the end of AIDS in our lifetime, and calls on world leaders to:

Embrace meaningful partnerships — especially with people living with #HIV and key populations;
 
Support global HIV research;
 
Prioritize HIV prevention;
 
Protect human rights;
 
And reject the politicization of science and scientificinstitutions.
 
I thank the Government of #Rwanda for hosting this important meeting, and I am pleased that it’s taking place in my home, Africa.

The BRICS leaders’ have demonstrated their dedication to health in a strong #BRICS2025 declaration. My thanks to the Presidents, Prime Ministers and Foreign Minister for reaffirming:
- their support to @WHO, including financial; 
- their commitment to the #PandemicAccord, including the negotiations for the Annex on Pathogen Access and Benefit-Sharing;
- their commitment to digital health and AI, healthy environments, to #EndTB and tackle antimicrobial resistance; 
- their commitment to universal health coverage and primary health care; 
- their commitment to disease prevention ahead of the #UNGA High-level meeting on noncommunicable diseases;
- their launch of the Partnership for the Elimination of Socially Determined Diseases;
- their commitment to ending poverty, social inclusion and health equity. 

Together, for #HealthForAll!

Great to see #Chile’s investment and focus on breast cancer prevention.

@WHO calls on all countries to strengthen access and affordability to screening for all women. 

https://t.co/WEcnNBNdiL

The partnership between @Rotary and @WHO goes back since 1988. In fact, Rotary were the pathfinders in first proposing the #EndPolio idea – inspired by the historic eradication of smallpox.

And today, we are on the cusp of history, despite the setbacks. 

Rotarians are showing what the world can be:

A world where courage defeats fear;

Where community defeats indifference;

Where determination defeats disease;

Where peace defeats war;

A world where your motto – service above self – really matters.
